	"__INITIAL_DATA__": {"comments":{"id":18039,"count":303,"talk_id":1668},"threadId":18039,"current_talk":"1668","description":"James Glattfelder studies complexity: how an interconnected system -- say, a swarm of birds -- is more than the sum of its parts. And complexity theory, it turns out, can reveal a lot about how the world economy works. Glattfelder shares a groundbreaking study of how control flows through the global economy, and how concentration of power in the hands of a shockingly small number leaves us all vulnerable.","event":"TEDxZurich 2012","language":"en","name":"James B. Glattfelder: Who controls the world?","slug":"james_b_glattfelder_who_controls_the_world","speakers":[{"id":"1541","slug":"james_b_glattfelder","is_published":true,"firstname":"James B.","lastname":"Glattfelder","middleinitial":"","title":"","description":"Complex systems theorist","photo_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/de3e0a608b7f913bd4e64c7cefe0ef94599cc108_254x191.jpg","whatotherssay":"As protests against financial power sweep the world this week, science may have confirmed the protesters' worst fears. An analysis of the relationships between 43,000 transnational corporations has identified a relatively small group of companies, mainly banks, with disproportionate power over the global economy ... The study, by a trio of complex systems theorists at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich, is the first to go beyond ideology to empirically identify such a network of power.","whotheyare":"James B. Glattfelder aims to give us a richer, data-driven understanding of the people and interactions that control our global economy. He does this not to push an ideology -- but with the hopes of making the world a better place.","whylisten":"<p>First a physicist and then a researcher at a Swiss hedge fund, James B. Glattfelder found himself amazed by the level of understanding we have in regards to the physical world and universe around us. He wondered: how can we move toward a similar understanding of human society?</p>  <p>This question led him to the study of complex systems, a subject he now holds a Ph.D in from the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology. Glattfelder is co-head of quantitative research at Olsen Ltd in Zurich, an FX investment manager focusing on market-stabilizing algorithms. In 2011, he co-authored the study &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0025995\" target=\"_blank\">The Network of Global Corporate Control</a>,&rdquo; which went viral in the international media and sparked many controversial discussions. The study looked at the architecture of ownership across the globe, and computed a level of control exerted by each international player. The study revealed that less than 1% of all the players in the global economy are part of a highly interconnected and powerful core which, because of the high levels of overlap, leaves the economy vulnerable.</p> <p>In his free time, Glattfelder enjoys snowboarding, rock climbing, surfing and listening to electronic music.&nbsp;</p>"}],"url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/james_b_glattfelder_who_controls_the_world","viewed_count":2612707,"talks":[{"recommendations":{"status":"approved","headline":"James Glattfelder recommends","blurb":"The complexity theorist shares further reading on the fundamental principles that run our economy.","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":null,"type":"recommendation","rec_lists":[{"title":"reading list","description":"","rec_items":[{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"The Network of Global Corporate Control","blurb":"","note":"Stefania Vitali et al.\r\n*PLOS One*, October 26, 2011","link_url":"http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0025995","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"Don't Follow the Leader\r\n","blurb":"","note":"*The Huffington Post*\r\nCosta Michailidis, March 7, 2013","link_url":"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/costa-michailidis/leadership-skills_b_2803858.html","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"To Navigate Economic Storms, We Need Better Forecasting","blurb":"","note":"Andy Haldane\r\n*New Scientist*, December 13, 2011","link_url":"http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg21228425.400-to-navigate-economic-storms-we-need-better-forecasting.html","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"The 147 Companies that Sort of Control Sort of Everything","blurb":"","note":"Bruce Upbin\r\n*Forbes*, November 21, 2011","link_url":"http://www.forbes.com/sites/bruceupbin/2011/11/21/the-147-companies-that-sort-of-control-sort-of-everything-full-list-revealed/","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"Revealed: The capitalist network that runs the world","blurb":"","note":"Andy Coghlan and Debora MacKenzie\r\n*New Scientist*, October 24, 2011","link_url":"http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg21228354.500-revealed--the-capitalist-network-that-runs-the-world.html","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"WATCH","headline":"James Glattfelder: How to build an economic system we actually understand","blurb":"","note":"*Wired* Money Talk, 2014","link_url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0llRJwA0ahA","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"Response to: The network of global corporate control ","blurb":"","note":"j-node, August 23, 2011","link_url":"http://j-node.blogspot.ch/2011/08/network-of-global-corporate-control.html","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"Ownership networks and corporate control: Mapping economic power in a\r\nglobalized world","blurb":"","note":"James B. Glattfelder\r\nETH Zurich, 2010","link_url":"http://www.sg.ethz.ch/media/medialibrary/2013/12/james_glatteth-2007-02.pdf","position":null,"is_pdf":true,"eyebrow":null}]}]},"more_resources":[{"status":"approved","headline":"*Decoding Complexity*","blurb":null,"link_url":"http://www.amazon.com/Decoding-Complexity-Uncovering-Patterns-Economic/dp/3642334237/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","image_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/8bbbc9d011d29458dbc3072e0b7567c5d275f374_438x664.jpg","author":"James B. Glattfelder","year":"2012","publisher":"Springer","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":null,"type":"book"}],"corrections":[{"timecode":"03:49","text":"I unfortunately lost my train of thought, which results in the cut here. What I wanted to say:\r\n\"This means you can forget about the equations and just start to understand the system by looking at the interactions. You can then understand the complex system by simulating it in a computer. As an example, you need three simple rules to simulate swarming behavior: Move in the same direction as your neighbor, stay close to your neighbor, but avoid collisions. If you think this is no big deal, think again. No one saw this coming. And to this day no one really knows why this is the way things are. It's as if reality is giving us a big help in understanding how stuff works. Like the 'miracle' I mentioned before, those equations mirror the workings of the universe. And it gets even better, because most complex systems have this amazing property called emergence. So this means that the system as a whole suddenly starts to show a behavior which cannot be understood or predicted by looking at the components of the system.\"","status":"approved","published":true,"type":"correction"},{"timecode":"08:11","text":"I misspoke when I said, \"Thirty-six percent of the TNCs are in the core only ... .\" Instead, I meant to say, \"Thirty-six percent of the TNCs are in the *center* only.\"","status":"approved","published":true,"type":"correction"}],"has_citations":true,"take_action":[],"curator_approved":true,"description":"J